    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-10T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-10T13:00:00-05:00" n="294"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d294">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4103: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain (<persName corresp="#p_AR1"
                            type="from">Atherton</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-10T18:00:00+00:00"
                            >February 10, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 10—2:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>59. Apparently to forestall questions for necessity of further representations to
                    Tokyo, and yet at the same time to have a clear record before the House of
                    Commons, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BSA1">Baldwin</persName>, in reply to a
                    question, stated yesterday: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“His Majesty’s Government have on three occasions made it clear to the
                            Japanese Government that they could not approve of the use of the
                            International Settlement except for defensive purposes.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>In referring to the above statement today <persName corresp="#p_VSRG1"
                        >Vansittart</persName> said the British Consul General at Shanghai favored
                    the creation of a neutral zone since it offered the greatest safety to the
                    International Settlement and the Foreign Office desired for the moment anyway to
                    leave attendant matters in the hands of the men on the spot, particularly since
                    the arrival of <persName corresp="#p_NVAK1">Admiral Nomura</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Atherton</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
